1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:04,522
So carrying on with these words, look at these two words called Nama and Rupa.

2
00:00:07,009 --> 00:00:14,647
Nama refers to mind and it comes right through to our language through

3
00:00:15,420 --> 00:00:20,350
through Latin, nomen, nat, the word name actually comes from the word nama.

4
00:00:20,931 --> 00:00:23,134
So it's basically referring to the mind.

5
00:00:23,535 --> 00:00:30,547
And rupa, actually its definition is really more to do with form, appearance, but basically it's the body.

6
00:00:32,450 --> 00:00:40,905
And it's understood that these are two different energies, two different forms of energy we can say.

7
00:00:41,408 --> 00:00:49,179
So that in later works it was said that in one material moment the mind arose 17 times.

8
00:00:49,219 --> 00:00:57,871
So there were 17 consciousnesses within the arising of one particular material moment.

9
00:00:57,890 --> 00:01:01,796
But we needn't worry too much about that.

10
00:01:02,097 --> 00:01:12,870
it begins in the dependent origination as you know, as we go through it, the first of coming into this life is this nāma-rupa, there's a split there, it's the body and mind.

11
00:01:14,692 --> 00:01:22,602
And in terms of the process of insight, in terms of the process of awakening,

12
00:01:23,156 --> 00:01:29,486
Remember that the Buddha's main technique is this process of deconstructing what we are.

13
00:01:30,308 --> 00:01:43,748
It's sort of looking at our experience and trying to find out its components to see whether any of these components or parts actually constitute anything real, anything substantial, something that

14
00:01:44,150 --> 00:02:13,919
doesn't arise and pass away basically so the first thing in our meditation is to make this distinction between this is the body this is the mind and to see them as two very separate perceptions so when you're watching the breath there's the rising and falling of the body the abdomen is rising and falling that's physicality and the actual naming of it rising and falling or the seeing of it is to do with the mind

15
00:02:15,959 --> 00:02:23,451
When you actually look at the Beth a bit more closely, you may find that the mind is also constructing the whole process.

16
00:02:23,992 --> 00:02:27,239
So there's an image of the stomach in the mind for a start.

17
00:02:27,258 --> 00:02:31,366
If you're watching it there, if you're watching it at the nostrils, it's the nostrils.

18
00:02:32,367 --> 00:02:35,413
And there's also this whole idea that something's rising and falling.

19
00:02:35,592 --> 00:02:36,715
So where does that come from?

20
00:02:36,816 --> 00:02:40,481
It comes from the mind actually contacting the body

21
00:02:40,764 --> 00:02:46,132
and through its own processes, feeling that rising and falling process.

22
00:02:46,492 --> 00:02:52,280
But actually what's coming from the body is just sensations, just sensations.

23
00:02:52,300 --> 00:02:57,426
So it's when you look at, say, pain, so you might feel discomfort in your sitting.

24
00:02:59,270 --> 00:03:01,812
What part of it is the mind and what part is the body?

25
00:03:02,813 --> 00:03:07,700
So as you contact it and you're saying, pain, pain, the very word pain is coming from the mind.

26
00:03:08,743 --> 00:03:14,711
So as you go into the pain, you begin to discover its various constituents.

27
00:03:14,730 --> 00:03:17,675
It might just be heat, it might be pressure, it might be some other things.

28
00:03:17,995 --> 00:03:21,098
So you recognize that the pain is a mental construct.

29
00:03:21,819 --> 00:03:23,622
What the body is giving is just sensations.

30
00:03:25,104 --> 00:03:31,512
And when you react to pain, you're not reacting to the body, you're reacting to your concept about what the sensations are.

31
00:03:33,617 --> 00:03:40,186
So it's that sort of breaking up of our experience to trying to find out whether there's anything substantial.

32
00:03:40,225 --> 00:03:40,986
Where's the self?

33
00:03:41,467 --> 00:03:42,889
When I talk about me, where is it?

34
00:03:45,794 --> 00:03:47,635
When we're eating, you see.

35
00:03:47,656 --> 00:03:55,145
So to make a distinction between the actual taste coming from the tongue and the delight that arises in the heart.

36
00:03:55,164 --> 00:03:59,030
I mean, most times when we eat, it's just all one experience.

37
00:03:59,191 --> 00:04:03,455
So as you put the food on your tongue, there's sensations arising.

38
00:04:04,296 --> 00:04:10,705
But then somehow when these sensations come into the mind, the mind immediately distinguishes it as pizza or something.

39
00:04:12,046 --> 00:04:13,830
But actually the taste has nothing to do with pizza.

40
00:04:13,870 --> 00:04:16,333
The taste is either salty or tomatoey or whatever it is.

41
00:04:16,574 --> 00:04:18,096
But it's not pizza.

42
00:04:18,456 --> 00:04:19,516
The mind says it's pizza.

43
00:04:19,577 --> 00:04:27,208
I mean, it's seen it, of course, but I'm just saying if you hadn't seen it and just put it in your tongue, then the mind would recognize these things as pizza.

44
00:04:27,228 --> 00:04:28,870
It's coming from its own memory bank.

45
00:04:29,288 --> 00:04:30,730
But more than that, it's reacting.

46
00:04:30,891 --> 00:04:33,716
So I don't know about you, but if I eat pizza, I feel delightful.

47
00:04:33,896 --> 00:04:35,600
It's just a natural occurrence.

48
00:04:35,959 --> 00:04:39,387
Because in the past, I've always had this pizza and it's always made me delighted.

49
00:04:40,168 --> 00:04:40,728
It's very simple.

50
00:04:41,110 --> 00:04:43,935
But the delight is nothing to do with the pizza.

51
00:04:44,495 --> 00:04:45,999
It's to do with my relationship with the pizza.

52
00:04:46,860 --> 00:04:48,663
If I didn't like pizza, I wouldn't feel happy.

53
00:04:49,235 --> 00:05:08,913
So it's making that distinction, it's actually pulling things apart that we begin to realise that this whole experience that we're having is not a me, it's a construct, it's a compendium of things that we put together into a concept, an actual experiential concept, and then we make the mistake of taking it as me.

54
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:17,285
Now there are two distinctions to be made.

55
00:05:17,425 --> 00:05:32,791
Once we've separated out this body and mind, once we've become clear that there is the body which is offering sensations, full stop, that's all it can do, and this is the mind which is interpreting it and reacting to it and has a relationship with it,

56
00:05:32,771 --> 00:05:40,029
It's then recognizing that there's some relationship going on, that the one arises dependent on the other.

57
00:05:40,672 --> 00:05:43,959
So when you put food on the tongue, the mind reacts.

58
00:05:44,261 --> 00:05:46,547
If you don't put food on the tongue, the mind doesn't react.

59
00:05:46,567 --> 00:05:47,389
It just doesn't happen.

60
00:05:48,247 --> 00:05:50,110
When the mind moves, the body moves.

61
00:05:50,449 --> 00:05:53,634
So as soon as you get an angry thought, there's something happens in the body.

62
00:05:54,055 --> 00:05:55,358
It reacts with heat.

63
00:05:56,559 --> 00:06:05,752
As soon as you have a fearful thought, it reacts with certain sensations, a wobbliness or a weak at the knees or nausea or whatever.

64
00:06:06,593 --> 00:06:18,050
So it's also catching that relationship between the body and mind that they are two separate things and yet you cannot actually separate them because they're both firing off the other at the same time.

65
00:06:19,279 --> 00:06:44,899
and this insight is the beginning of the process of investigating this human phenomena to see whether there's anything actually substantial within it so in terms of the process of insight through the vipassana these are your first two insights and it's this what raises the curiosity to go into it more deeply

66
00:06:47,107 --> 00:06:53,696
So nama-rupa, this body and mind, are really the beginning of your practice.

67
00:06:54,076 --> 00:06:55,278
That's what you're asked to do.

68
00:06:55,879 --> 00:07:02,827
The beginning of your practice is to make this very clear distinction in ourselves.

69
00:07:02,848 --> 00:07:07,875
I can only hope that this little homily has brought amazing insight.

70
00:07:09,456 --> 00:07:14,463
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

